The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (MHLW) announced on September 26, the first time that 424 hospitals in 1455 public hospitals and public hospitals in Japan, including Japan and the Red Cross, judged that their medical records were poor.
In Fukui Prefecture, the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare verified the medical record of 14 public and public hospitals, and the four facilities were targeted: Awara Hospital, the National Hospital Organization of the City of straw, and Awara Hospital, the City of Sakai Three Kingdom Hospital, and the Oda Hospital in Echizen Town, the Wakasa Takahama Hospital.
⇒ Four hospitals subject to reorganization "Standard Funny"
In order to reduce medical expenses that are expanding due to the aging population, it was necessary to encourage the reorganization and integration of hospitals in competing areas.
In October, we will request a full-scale review of reorganization and integration at the target hospital, and we will conclude by September next year.
Although there is no compulsion, it is expected that local chiefs and residents will be repulsed due to anxiety that hospitals nearby will disappear.
It was announced at the meeting on the same day.
The total number of hospitals was 29-1 percent, with relatively few beds.
By prefecture, the percentage was high in Niigata (53,7%), Hokkaido (48,6%), Miyagi (47,5%), Yamaguchi (46,7%), and Okayama (43,3%).
The number of targets was 54 in Hokkaido, and Okinawa was the only zero.
Based on data from FY2017, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare investigated 1455 hospitals that can respond to "altitude acute phase" for severe patients and "acute phase" for general surgery.
He analyzed nine medical records, including cancer and emergency medical care, and whether competing hospitals were located within 20 minutes by car.
The hospital should be considered to be abolished and some medical departments are transferred to other hospitals.
Medical expenses increased rapidly in 25 years, when all baby boomers were over 75 years old.
For this reason, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare has set a goal of reducing the number of beds in hospitals in Japan to 12.46 thousand beds (18 years).
Currently, there are many beds in the "Advanced Acute" and "Acute" periods where nurses are placed thickly and medical expenses are required, while there is a shortage of rehabilitation services for elderly people with high needs.
In order to cope with the aging population, it is necessary not only to reduce the number of beds, but also to increase rehabilitation.
In order to reorganize and integrate the hospital, each prefecture formulated a "regional medical plan" that defined the number of beds required for 25 years.
It is divided into 339 parts of the country, with municipalities and medical officials discussing it, but many local residents and chiefs maintain their cautious stance, and discussions are difficult.
The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare wants to revitalize the discussion by publishing the name of a hospital with poor results.
Comprehensive training for disaster prevention such as the assumption of Mt.Komake eruption, road etc.
On September 27, a comprehensive disaster prevention drill was held in the forest, Nanae and Kabe-cho in the Toshima-kan.
Approximately 400 people from 20 organizations and residents attended the event.
The first event since the Hokkaido Komagatake Volcano Disaster Prevention Council formulated an evacuation plan incorporating evacuation routes for residents in August.
It was the first time in 18 years that residents participated in extensive training.
At 8:45 a.m., Mt.Komake erupted and the mud flow reached the town at the foot of the mountain.
When the eruption alert level was raised to 5 (evacuation), shelters were opened in forests and Nanae Ryocho, and residents moved by buses and police cars prepared by each town.
