Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Gifu Shimbun Web) - Yahoo!
On September 27, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries released a draft amendment to the Anti-Defection Guidelines to prevent the spread of "Tonn cholera" (porks) that are not currently recognized.
The target area is to select nine prefectures, including Gifu Prefecture and Aichi Prefecture, which have confirmed infection with pigs and wild boars.
Live pigs and fertilized eggs vaccinated are restricted to the region, but the distribution of meat and processed foods is permitted.
After public comments (approval of opinions) to the general public, we aim to complete the procedure in October as soon as possible.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterrestrial distribution such as meat, it is no longer a "clean country" certified by international organizations and may affect the export of pork.
Since the outbreak of September last year, Japan has been temporarily suspended.
With regard to areas with high risk of infection from wild boar to pigs, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries set up a recommended area for vaccination.
The target prefecture will create a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, time, number of heads, and how to proceed, and will be approved by the province and allowed to use it by the governor's decision.
Seven other prefectures in Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie and Shiga have been proposed as recommended areas for vaccination.
When the guidelines are revised, the region will make a very clear decision on the situation.
The movement of inoculated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, corpses, excreted objects, etc. is restricted to the region in principle.
As for meat and processed products, it is not targeted based on the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and it practically accepts distribution outside the region.
To prevent viruses from spreading, we will thoroughly process food waste.
He also advocates the safety of the inoculated pigs and works to prevent harmful rumors.
The revised guidelines were compiled at an expert meeting held on the same day and confirmed at a meeting of the Anti-Defection Control Headquarters.
In the future, opinions and public comments to prefectures will be conducted until October 7, and new guidelines will be enforced.
